{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_perry_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600313/1930122701/0434.xml":{"full_text":"REAL ESTATE\n11 PROGRESS MARKS 1930 REALTY BUSINESS IN GREATER WASHINGTON\nI FUNDAMENTAL CONDITIONS\nI SHOW REMARKABLE GAINS\nFewer New r Unsold Houses oil Market\nThan Year Ago and Apartment\nI* Vacancies Are at Low Point.\nBY DON S. WARREN,\nReal Estate. Editor of The Star.\nTHE stock market slump, national business depression and the\ndrought to the contrary, the real estate and construction\nindustry of Greater Washington made real progress during\nh the past year, and many impressive and lasting improvements\nWere added to the physical development of the Capital.\nWhile general conditions served to depress private construction\nprograms and sales transactions to some degree, the declines from\nlevels for 1929 were not nearly as great as many feared and, in fact,\nfundamental conditions showed remarkable improvement that augurs\nwell for the new year.\ngs The supply of new, unsold houses on the market is considerably\nlower than at the close of 1929, the percentage of apartment house\nVacancies is the lowest since post-war days, costs of building ma\nterials is down, the supply of building tradesmen is adequate and\nthe growth of population continues and standards of living are being\ntnaintained.\nGreater Activity Seen.\nAll this leads observers to predict increased activity for the new\ntoear, though not of the size or character that connotes a \u201cboom.\u2019*\n5 Exclusive of the Federal build-\nIng projects, the cost of which j\nruns into millions of dollars,!\nprivate construction programs in j\nthe District approved by the Dis-\ntrict building inspector during I\n1930 cost an estimated total of\n$28,804,452. This does not include j\ni the comparatively small figure!\nfor plans which may be approved J\nduring the last five days of the j\nJrear.\nThis figure, however, does not\nRepresent the full total of private\noperations actually started dur- i\ning the year, since three large I\nprojects, running to an estimated i\ntotal of $6,625,000 now are under j\nway with preliminary work in j\nprogress, although the projects j\nI have not been approved in full by j\nthe building inspector and there- i\nfore not included in the official\nl total.\nIncluding these projects as part of\nthe private construction that has been i\ncompleted or started during the past\nyear, the total is brought up to $35,-\n429,452. or but about $700,000 less than\nthe total of $36,129,765 for the year\n3929.\nThe three large projects, now in pre\nliminary state of construction, but for\nWhich official permits have not yet been\napproved, are the huge apartment hotel\nbeing erected by Kenney-Warren, Inc.,\non a large site on the east side of Con\nnecticut avenue, near Klingle Valley\nBridge, the construction cost being\nestimated at $3,250,000; the third\nbuilding of the Westchester Apartments\ndevelopment on the 28-acre tract along\nCathedral avenue between Thirty-ninth\nstreet and Glover Parkway, estimated\nto cost $3,000,000; and the church\nbuilding for the Latter Day Saints be\ning erected on the southwest comer of\nSixteenth street and Columbia road at\ncost estimated at $400,000.\nV Conditions Are Improved.\nImprovements in fundamental condi\ntions in the real estate business during\nthe past year is clearly shown in sur\nveys made by Rufus S. Lusk, Inc., local\nstatistical organization headed by Rufus\n6. Lusk, the secretary of the Operative\n{Builders\u2019 Association.\nThese surveys show as of the first of\nDecember, this year, there was a\nsmaller number of new, unsold houses\non the market than at the same time\nlast year, and a considerably lower per\ncentage of vacancies in apartments, due\nto the growth of the population and the\ndecline in new residential construction\nduring the past two years.\nThis is a good thing for the public\nfcnd the city as a whole, as well as in\nvestors in real estate, since an unwield\nly oversupply of housing, while serving\nusually to force down sale and rent\nprices, reacts in depressing property\nValues generally.\nThat there is a normal quantity of\nUnsold new houses and vacant apart\nments on hand also is regarded as a\ngood thing for the public, since if the\ndemand is greater than the supply of\nhousing, the usual tendency is a rise\nfin prices and rents which may not ac\ncurately reflect the rise in property\nvalues.\n7.1 Per Cent Apartment Vacancy.\nThe current surveys by Lusk show\nthat 7.1 per cent of apartment units in\nWashington were vacant and that there\nwere 984 new. unsold houses on the\nmarket. The survey of apartment va\ncancies covers the majority of all\napartments in the city and the house\nsurvey covers all new houses started\nduring the year.\nThese figures reveal an encouraging\nchange from conditions that existed at\nthe first of December, last year, when\nthe vacancies in apartments was found\nto be 9 9 per cent and the number of\nunsold new houses on the market to\nbe 1,116. Both figures for this year are\nlower than in 1928.\nThis represents the readjustment\nthat has been in progress during the\npast year as builders and financiers,\neither by careful planning or from the\neffect of the general business depres\nsion, curtailed the total amount of new\nhousing construction started during the\nyear.\nThe Lusk surveys show a total during\nthe past year cf 74 apartment buildings,\ncontaining 949 apartment units, the I\nconstruction cost being estimated at\n$6,111,150. In 1929. the corresponding\nfigures were 56 apartment buildings\ncontaining *,9tW units, cosring $9,658,-\n500.\nDuring the past year, the Lusk sur-\nFoxhall Village\nA Quaint Colony of Homes\nAdjoining Georgetown\nOs the West\u2014Only 10\n\"Minutes from City\n5 and 6 Bed Rooms\n3 Tiled Baths\nLarge Studio and\nLounge Rooms\n$17,750 to $24,500\nThe rtotnes of l oxhall Village\nwere not created nor are they\ndeveloped as residences for a\nswiftly y*\u00bb,jing year or two.\nSubstantially as well as beau\ntifully built, they will .stand\nfirmly through the years to\ncome.\nYou Will Be Charmed With This\nModel Home, 1606 44th St\nOpen 9 A M. Until 6 P.M.\nFurnished by Sloane\nBOSS PHELPS.\n1417 K St. NAtienal 9394\nDrive out Oue st. to Wls. eve.: north\n1 block to Reservoir r\u00abi.: west to VII\nlace- Turn lelt on *4th st. to home\n9 on west atd\u00ab.\nWASHINGTON, D. U.,\nI veys show, 957 houses were started, j\ni costing $7,482,500 as compared with\n1,403 houses costing $11,124,032 started\nduring the year 1929.\nApril Biggest Month,\ni How private building operations pro\ngressed during the past year is shown\nin the official monthly statements issued\nby Col. John W. Oehmann, building\ninspector, as follows:\nJanuary $4,540,170\nFebruary 857,170\nMarch 3.083,040\nApril 4.778,720\nMay 3,032,412\nJune 1,613.055\nJuly 2,356,570\nAugust 2.396,620\nSeptember 1,077,810\nOctober 2,191.665 i\nNovember 1,477.220\nDecember (incomplete) 1.400,000\nTotal $28,804,452 j\nThis total does not include the three\nprojects now actually under way, but j\nwhich are not included in the official\npermit total because plans have not\nbeen approved as an entity, which\nbrings the total of work started in 1930\nto $35,429,452.\nOfficial totals for the preceding 11\nyears are as folfows:\nEstimated I\nValue of\nTear. Work. I\n1919 ..p. $20,300,000\n1920 19.500.000\n1921 24,400.000\n1922 49 000,000\n1923 50.500,000\n1924 46,800,000 j\n1925 64,610,513 I\n1926 63,499,330\n1927 36.321.450\n1928 51,255,080\n1929 36,129,765\nNumbers of large real estate transac\ntions took place, some of which are\nlisted here. At the start of the year\nParker-Bridget Co., veteran Washing\nton clothiers, signed a lease for first\nfloor space in the Washington Building,\nwhich it has since occupied. The In\nvestment Building, Fifteenth and K\nstreets, was acquired by the Continental\nBuilding, Inc., from the Washington\nBuilding Corporation for a considera\ntion reported to exceed $3,000,000;\nJames B. Sparks was reported the pur\nchaser of the large commercial garage\nbuilding at Twenty-first and L streets;\ninterests associated v.ith the Commer\ncial National Bank acquired the for\nmer Union Savings Bank Building at\n710 Fourteenth street; the Willard j\nApartment Co.. Inc., purchased the\nlarge Chalfonte Apartments, formerly\nknown as Phillips Terrace, for a con\nsideration reported to be $1,500,000; the\nShell Eastern Petroleum Products Co.\nentered the local field with the acquisi\ntion of a large number of filling station\nproperties; the American Oil Co. pur\nchased 65 service stations in or near\nWashington for a large consideration,\nand the Texas Co. purchased approxi\nmately a dozen filling station prop\nerties.\nBig Building Sold.\nOne of the largest realty deals was\nthe purchase of the Shoreham Office\nBuilding, northwest corner of Fifteenth\nand H streets, on the site of the famous\nold Shoreham Hotel, by Joseph Irwin\nCromwell, Southwest oil magnate, so\u00bb\na reported consideration of $3,750,000.\nThe business property at 1307 F street\nwas purchased for a consideration of\n$300,000 by John H. Harriett, former\nGovernor of New Hampshire. The\nHurley-Wright Building, 12-story office\nstructure on the southwest corner of\nEighteenth street and Pennsylvania\navenue, was purchased from Patrick J.\nHurley, now Secretary of War, by a\ngroup of local investors.\nPresaging a new development for\nPennsylvania avenue, the property\nfronting on the east side of Thirteenth\nstreet and extending also along the\nAvenue and E street was purchased by\n(Continued on Sixth Page.)\nJust Think of It\nThe Star delivered to your\ndoor every evening and Sunday\nmorning at per day and 5c\nSunday. Can you afford to be\nwitheut this service at this cost?\nTelephone National 5000 and de\nlivery will start at once.\n<?2 The Christmas Lights in\nShepherd Park\nare well worth your visit.\nDrive out 16th St. to Alasha\nAve., then out Alasha Ave. to\nHemloch St., turn left into Sheft-\nS herJPark s\nWhile in Shepherd Park Visit 5\nOur Furnished Home Bf\n7611 14th St. N.W.\nThe large lighted Christmas tree on the |f\nlawn is indicative of the Christmas spirit which 10?\nprevails here. 5r\n\u00a3\u00a3ffortumnser Sons\nftjr Builders\u2014Realtors ST\nn Investment Bldg. National 2040\nARLINGTON PLANS\nBIG REALTY YEAR\n1930 Behind Previous Period\nin Building, With Schools\nHeading List.\nBY LESTER N. INSKEEP,\nStaff Correspondent of The Star\nARLINGTON COUNTY COURT\nHOUSE, Va., December 27.\u2014Arlington\nCounty approaches the end of the year\nsomewhat behind last year\u2019s building\nmark, but with what local realtors term\nas a \u201cbright outlook\u2019\u2019 for the coming\nyear.\nThe largest building program at\ntempted during the year is in the hands\nof the School Board, which is erecting\nadditions to the Washington-Lee High\nSchool and four of the elementary\nschools that will cost more than $300,-\n000. The funds for this purpose were\nmade available through a bond issue\nthat carried by a large majority.\nSeveral New Churches.\nThere have been several churches\nconstructed, among which are a Baptist\nchurch in Virginia Highlands and a\nPresbyterian church in Arlington. There\nalso have been improvements and ad\nditions to several religious institutions\nthroughout the county.\nThe Jargest privately owned building\nerected during the year is the new\nstructure in Clarendon in which is\nhoused the Clarendon branch of the\nWashington Post Office. The Ballston\nbranch also has been provided with\nnew quarters.\nAmong the new business activities are\nthe formation of the Rucker Lumber\nCo. at Rosslyn, and also the purchase\nof an extensive building there by Rose*\nBrothers of Washington. The latter\nfirm is moving its roofing business to\nthe Virginia terminus of the Key j\nBridge.\nThe Army-Navy Country Club at j\nArlington has erected two large exten-\nsions during the year and now has one\nof the largest club buildings in the\ni vicinity of Washington.\nSpurred on by the continuous\nI drought, the county water department\nhas put in 12 miles of water exten\nsions, at an approximate cost of $155,-\n000. thereby increasing the demand for\nwater to the 1,000.000-gallon daily ca\npacity of the main from the Federal\nreservoir.\nCounty road work has included the\nsurface treating of approximately 50\nmiles of already existing roads and\nstreets and the construction of 3 miles\nof new roads. Most of this development j\nhas taken place in Jefferson district, j\nI where a large proportion of the\u2019 half\nmillion dollars received from Alexan\ndria in the annexation proceedings will\nI be expended.\nPike Is Improved.\nThe State Highway Commission wid-\nI ened and rebuilt the Washington-Alex\nandria pike from South Washington to\nFour Mile Run, the new corporate lim\nits of Alexandria, and surface treated\nGlebe road from Columbia pike to the\nAlexandria line. An additional SIOO,OOO\nhas been allocated for the Lee Boule\nvard construction, bringing the total\namount appropriated for this work to\ndate to $200,000.\nThere has been a decided improve\nment during the year at the Virginia\nend of the Highway Bridge, largely\nthrough the construction program of\nI the Washington Airport, which has\nI done away with the old amusement\npark there and generally eliminated\neyesores of years\u2019 standing.\nR. D. KOHN HONORED\nRobert D. Kohn, president of the\nj American Institute of Architects, has!\nbeen elected an honorary corresponding\nmember of the Royal Institute of Brit\nish Architects, according to word re\nceived here.\nStart\nThe New Year Right\nin a\nCafritz Lifetime Home\nAn Incomparable Value\n20 ft. wide\u2014lot ft. deef>\nBig rooms\u20143 large porches\nScreened throughout\nHardwood trim, cedar closet\nKelvinator\u2014Garage\nSSOO Cash\nEasy Monthly Payments\nExhibit Ho me\n422 Farragut St. N.W.\nOpen until 9 P.M.\nCAFRITZ\n14th K Diet. 9080 j\nlEtieumg Jifaf.\nBUILDING PACE MAINTAINED\nIN SUBURBAN MONTGOMERY\nPermits Issued for Nearly $2,000,000 in\nConstruction Projects for Two\nMetropolitan Districts.\nBY WILLIAM S. TARVER,\nStaff Correspondent of The Star.\nBuilding operations in suburban\nMontgomery County continued on an\neven keel during 1930, apparently but\nlittle affected by the general business\ndepression, with permits for almost\n$2,000,000 worth of construction work\nissued by building inspectors of the two\nmetropolitan districts, Takoma Park\nand Kensington.\nRoad construction remained almost at\na standstill, although the $200,000\nBethesda-Silver Spring highway, almost\ncompleted in 1929. was formally opened\nto traffic early in 1930. The only other\nnotable highway development was the\n1.4 miles of road, built by the Maryland-\nNational Capital Park and Planning\nCommission, which opens up the eastern\nend of Sligo Valley in Montgomery\nCounty for park use. The road- con\nnects Takoma Park and Silver Spring,\nparalleling the creek, and will cost\nabout $25,000 when it is finished shortly\nafter January 1, according to official\nestimates.\nPrivate operations west of Rock Creek,\nwhich divides the two metropolitan dis\ntricts, far exceeded in value develop\nments on the eastern side of the county,\nrockvillTsets\nBUILDING RECORD\nConstruction of Court House,\nBanks and Church Bring\nTotal to New High.\nBY CAREY KINGDON,\nBtaff Correspondent of The Star\nROCKVILLE, Md, December 27.\nThe aggregate value of construction\nwork undertaken In Rockville during\n1930 is in excess of best previous figures\nattained in the history of the town, a\ncompilation of the year's building activ\ni ities reveals.\nPublic building projects, principally\nin the form of the $400,000 combination\ncourt house and jail, started during the\nyear, constituted the major portion of\nthe high total of between $700,000 and\nSBOO,OOO worth of new projects.\nRanking second in importance to the\ncourt house is the new structure erected j\nby the Farmers\u2019 Banking Sc Trust Co., j\nwhich was recently completed at a cost\nof $120,000. An addition to the Mont\ngomery County National Bank, coupled\nwith extensive improvements being un- i\ndertaken on the present building, rep\nresents an expenditure of approximately\n$50,000.\nA handsome church edifice in the\nform of a naw home for the Presby-\nj terian Church here was erected during\nthe year at a cost of more than $25,000.\nExtensive remodeling and improve\nment work was undertaken during the\nyear by a number of private concerns,\nincluding the Brosius, Gormley Sc Bro\nsius, automobile dealers, establishment,\nwhich represented an outlay of several\nthousand dollars. Many private resi\ndences were erected or improved and\nrenovation work undertaken on many\nof the town\u2019s important business houses.l\nStart the New Year Right\nBUY\nA Home of Your Own\nThat Is Built to Endure\nTWO CHOICE LOCATIONS\n1702 C St. N.E. 1223 Owen PI. N.E.\nrsim\nspacious rooms, tiled bath with north of 13th and Florida ave. Six\nj shower; garage Attractively fur- large rooms, tiled bath, garage.\nnished. with hardwood floors, pan- _, _\neled walls, handsome figures, and t*\u2122** ll pav Substan-\nFrigidaire. ttally built, and artistically finished.\nOpen Daily Until 9 P.M.\nLow Price, Small Gash Payment\nMODERATE TERMS\nR. E. KLINE, Jr., Owner\n718 Union Trust Building National 6799\nOr Any Broker\nPlan for the New Year NOW\nInspect our neic\nCOMMUNITY GROUP\nof Ultra-Modern All-Brick Homes\nEXHIBIT HOME\n335 Concord Ave. N.W.\nAt 4th and Longfellow Streets\nOpen every day until 9 P.M.\nIf you\u2019ve resolved to become a home owner\nduring the New Year we urge your Immedt\nqQ AfA ate inspection of this new group\u2014while\nHjll UP varied types and designs are available. Six\nvjivvv large rooms, front and screened double rear\nporches, built-in garages, complete tile baths,\ndouble oak floors, natural trim, cedar closets;\nelectric refrigeration, Sanitas wall covering,\ndouble drainboard sink and unusual type\nTO dressers In kitchens. Also one corner home\n1 u containing four bed rooms, and several semi-\nStreet ice- detached houses at slightly higher prices.\nnue to Longfellow St., Homes are fully screened and have beautt\nthence east to houses. fully finished interiors. Some have fire\nor take 14th St. <Ta\nkoma Park) car line P*aces.\nto Longfellow St. This group faces 120-ft. boulevard that con\nnects Rock Creek and Fort Slocum Parks.\nOne block 14th St. car line\u2014near excellent\nschools, etc.\n1418 H.G. Smithu Co. Nan\nr NICIItM T, UIIMK. /M nnl\nE 7 e St\n\nalthough the individual projects were\nalmost equal in number.\nApproximately $1,124,000 worth of\nbuilding permits were issued by J. Fred\nImlrie, building inspector for the west\nern district, while Martin Iverson, in\nspector for the eastern district, author\ned operations costing $602,110. In ad\ndition, building in Takoma Park and\nKensington, both of which are incorpo\nrated town\u00a7, amounted to approximately\nSIOO,OOO in value.\nThe largest single project during the\nyear was the Baptist Memorial Home\nfor Children in Alta Vista, which is to\ncost $150,000 when completed. A resi\ndence on the Rockville pike about naif\na mile north of Bethesda is to cost\n$150,000.\nThe most costly enterprise in the\neastern district was the Episcopal\nChurch of the Ascension, on Blair road,\nwhich cost approximately $40,000.\nProbably the most important develop\nment planned for 1931 is the conver\nsion of the southern end of Rock Creek\nValley in Montgomery County into a\npark to connect with Rock Creek Park\nin the District of Columbia. The Mary\nland-National Capital Park and Plan-\nning Commission expects to have the 1\nsection opened up as far as Wisconsin\navenue near Garrett Park before the\nyear ends.\nALEXANDRIA SEES\nGROWING ACTIVITIES\nPrivate Construction for\n1930 Shows Drop\u2014Big Proj\nects Will Start Soon.\nBY HOWARD M. BAGGETT,\nStaff Correspondent of The Star.\nALEXANDRIA, Va., December 27.\nThis city, at the conclusion of a suc\ncessful year in the real estate field, Is\nlooking forward to unprecedented ac\ntivity in building construction during\nthe next 12 months, with work on the\nprojected Mount Vernon Boulevard\nforming an outstanding phase of the:\nprogram.\nPrivate building construction work\nand repairs during the past year\nreached an aggregate value of almost\n$500,000. The total value of permits\nissued for 1929, however, was $876,848.\nIn addition, a new Alexandria post\ni office and Federal building, represent-\nI ing an outlay of $250,000, has been\nstarted. An important factor in the\nforthcoming year\u2019s building program\nwill be the establishment of the by\n<Continued on Sixth Page.)\nDoable-Front English Group Ho\u00bbti\nFOXALL\nSix and Eight Rooms, one. two\nand three baths.\n$10,950 to $15,050\nModel Home. 1100 Volta\nPlace N.W.\nWAVERLY TAYLOR. JSs\ntffl K STOUT NATT t*M\nSATURDAY, DECEMBER 27. 10.20.\n1550* BUILDING\n1338 COUNTY MARK\nPrince Georges Much En\nhanced, Though Slightly\nUnder 1929 Record.\nBY GEORGE PORTER.\nStaff Correspondent of The Star\nUPPER MARLBORO, Md., December\n27. \u2014Construction programs, public and\nprivate, although not attaining the vol\nume reached in 1929, brought perma\nnent improvements to Prince Georges\nCounty during the past year that en\nhanced the physical appearance of the\narea. The total value of buildings au\nthorized is estimated at $550,000.\nPublic and semi-public building en\nterprises were quite numerous during\nthe year. High school buildings were\nerected in Mount Rainier and Bladens\nburg, while addition were made to pub\nlic school buildings in several commun\nities. At the University of Maryland a\nlarge, new library and a power plant\nwere built.\nNew Church Erected.\nA new Episcopal church was erected\nin College Park and a Sunday school\ni hall was added to the Mount Rainier\nMethodist Church.\n1 The Stephens Citizens\u2019 Association\ncompleted its community hall, while\nfire department buildings, which also\nare used for community gatherings,\nwere erected or are under way at Glen\ndale, Oxon Hill, Branchville and\nTuxedo.\nThe Odd Fellows completed a hall at\nBowie, while one fraternity and one\nsorority house were built in College\nPark.\nWork on Highways.\nThe largest public building operations\nwere carried on by the State Roads\nCommission, which widened the Balti\nmore boulevard to a width of 40 feet,\nthe Defense Highway to about 22 feet,\nand now is erecting a new $125,000\nbridge that will eliminate the danger\nous curve and bridge over the Penn\nsylvania Railroad track at Lanham.\nAs in 1929, there was practically no\nspeculative building and comparatively\nfew commercial structures were erected.\nThe largest of these was the new Hy\nattsville office of the Chesapeake Sc Po\ntomac Telephone Co. of Baltimore,\nwhich 1 was completed during the year.\nThe building which housed the old\nHyattsville exchange was razed and\nnow is being replaced by a modem drug\nstore. A few other stores were erected\nin the suburban area, and one or two\napartment houses.\nDuring the past month a $60,000 ho\ntel and office building for College Park\ni was authorized. Most of the other\nbuilding licenses .were issued for private\nresidences and alterations to existing\nstructures.\nTHE BEST BUY^\nIn Northeast Washington\nJameson Built Homes\n1504 d st. N.E.\nDesigned and built by experts according to the best\narchitectural standards. Nothing but carefullv\nselected materials of the highest quality and labor\nfurnished by skilled mechanics, have gone into the\nconstruction of these homes.\n7 large rooms, tile bath with built-in tub and\nshower, extra large porches front and rear, natural\nwood trim, Fngidaire and built-in garage.\n[Ask the Family Who Owns One!]\nOpen for Inspection\nWm. M. Throckmorton\n208 Investment Bldg. District 6093\npircatur S o6\u00bbo\nPROGRAM OF GOVERNMENT\nSPURS PRIVATE BUILDING\n\ni T\nNew Stores, Office Buildings, Churches,\nApartments and Schools Bring Total\nto Millions of Dollars.\nBY VINCENT TUTCHING.\nTHE gigantic public buildings program of the Federal Govern\nment, which in itself has contributed much to the beautifica\ntion of the Capital City, has also performed the dual function\ni of stimulating private construction and realty transactions\nin Washington during the year now ending.\nAs the Government has acquired more and more private prop\nerties, so also have scores of residences and business houses been\nforced from the area which is to form the site of the Federal\ndovelopment.\nConsiderable iucrease was thus brought to private activities dur\ning the year. At the same time private industry and private insti\ntutions have proceeded steadily with construction projests to lend\nimpetus to the transformation of the skyline of the city.\nNew Municipal Center.\nThe District government, which will be forced from its present\nlocation by the Federal program, has proceeded with the acquisition\nof properties in the new municipal center site\u2014between Third and\nSixth streets, Pennsylvania, Louisiana and Indiana avenues\u2014and\nrazing operations preparatory to its construction work there are to\nbe started during the New Year.\nAn outgrowth of the Govern-'\nment\u2019s acquisition of the property\non the south side of Fourteenth\nstreet at C street, which was pur\nchased from the Potomac Electric\nPower Co. in connection with the\nj triangle development program,\nwas the erection at Tenth and E\nstreets of the new $1,100,000 office\nbuilding of the power company,\ni In addition, the power firm spent\nj $300,000 for the construction of a\n4-story service building at Tenth\nstreet and Florida avenue.\nGarfinckel Store Outstanding.\nMany smaller concerns having plants\nand office headquarters south of Penn\nsylvania avenue in the path of the Fed\neral building program have moved else-\nI where, to the end that many new build\nings have been erected and are contem\nplated in various sections of the city.\nConstituting a high point in the phys\nical development of downtown Wash\nington, Julius Garfinckel Sc Co. this\nyear completed its new department store\nI building at Fourteenth and F streets.\nrepresenting one of the largest private\nundertakings in the central part of the\ni city in recent years.\nA development of monumental char\nacter which will add a new and impres\nsive landmark to the private develop-\nI ments of the National Capital is the\nShakespeare Memorial Library Building,\nerected by Henry C. Folger at 201 East\nCapitol street at a cost of $1,450,000.\nThe edifice is adjacent to the Congres\nsional Library and to properties recently\nBUILDING NEWS\nacquired by the Government for fir\u00bb\u00bb*\ndevelopment.\nNew units were added to the Wasn\nington Cathedral on Mount St. Alban\nand to the groups of buildings in Brook\nland belonging to Catholic institutions,\nincluding the National Shrine of the\nImmaculate Conception and the Holy\nName College Building.\nNew Apartment Buildings.\nNew apartment houses and new busi\nness structures were among some of the\noutstanding projects started or com\npleted during the year. Progress was\ncontinued in the development of resi\ndential sections in the District and there\nwas added growth to the suburban sec\ntions in Greater Washington outside the\nDistrict boundaries.\nOther major private building projects\n(Continued on Sixth Page.)\nj Buy a Home\nWith All Conveniences\n$7,650\np SAMPLE HOUSE\n1825 Bay St. S.E.\nBetween Huh. 111th. B C St*. S.E.\nP Near Eastern High School p\nV f\nOpen For Intpeetion\n6 P.M. to 9 P.M. Daily P\n1 And All Day Sundayu J\n\n6 rooms and bath\nGlass sleeping porch\nJ Front and rear porches r\nBath\u2014colored tile and shower f\nS Built-in tub S\nBuilt-in wall safe S\nMirror door\nf Built-in telephone closet i\nf Built-in folding ironing board\nCedar-lined closet\nG. E. electric clock p\n5 Hot-water heat\n5 Hot-water storage tank e\nt One-piece washing tub J\nP Panel wall paper J\nf Hardwood floors S\nHardwood trim\n5 Frigidaire p\nWalker electric dishwashar f\n1 Hardinge oil burner\nGARAGE p\nTERMS\u2014SSOO Cash f\ng S6O a Month\n(Includes Interest on Both Trusts) P\n2 Steuart Brothers\n2 Real Eetate Construction\n138 12th St. N.E.\nB-1","height":"25494","width":"19725"}}
